	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=/db/item.html?item=6836&mid=100310235698887>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=/db/item.html?item=6836&mid=100310235698887>On the subject of haste</a> <a id=fs8 href=/db/item.html?item=6836&mid=100310235698887#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Sun, Oct 14th 7:32 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=91990><span id= >Atmos</span></a><br><span id=notbold>26 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Haste IS an increase in damage dealt over a period of time. The way it was phrased by Cronuus is correct. You can use common sense to see why this is the way it works, because after all, if you got up to 100% haste (max at 60) and haste directly affected delay, then you'd have a 0 delay weapon, which we all know is impossible. Haste is in reality done the way it has been phrased, as a percent increase in your damage dealt over a period of time. The way your damage is increased is by lowering your delay by 100 divided by (100 + total haste percent) multiplied by the weapon's delay. Laters all, hope I cleared some stuff up. Nice bow too.</p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Atmos Phere, Monk of Rodcet Nife</td></tr>
